Our dataset contains counts of deaths and population at risk, as estimated by the Australian Bureau of Statistics\footnote{The data were downloaded from the database \emph{Deaths, Year of registration, Indigenous status, Age at death, Sex, Five State/Territory} on the ABS website, on 1 March 2019}. The data covers the period \Sexpr{time_min}--\Sexpr{time_max}, and is stratified by age at death, sex, indigenous status, state or territory, and year.  The age groups are \Sexpr{age_groups_head}, ..., \Sexpr{age_groups_tail}. The ABS omits the three Australian states or territories with the smallest number of indigenous people (Tasmania, Victoria, and the Australian Capital Territory) from the dataset. For indigenous deaths, the minimum cell size in the is \Sexpr{cell_min}, the maximum is \Sexpr{cell_max}, and the median is \Sexpr{cell_med}.

\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
     \includegraphics{out/fig_rates_direct_2016}
        \caption{Direct estimates of mortality rates, 2016. Log scale. The points along the bottom of the graph represent values that were 0 on the original scale, and hence are undefined on the log scale.}
      \label{fig:rates_direct_2016}
\end{figure}

Figure~\ref{fig:rates_direct_2016} show estimates of mortality rates in 2016, obtained using the traditional demographic approach of dividing death counts for each combination of stratifying variables by the associated population at risk. It is clear that indigenous mortality rates are higher than non-indigenous rates across all states and territories. There is, however, too much random variation to permit confident answers to questions such as as whether indigenous mortality rates are higher in some states than others.

Let $y_{asirt}$ denote deaths to people of age $a$, sex $s$, and indigenous status $i$, in state or territory $r$, during year $t$. Similarly, let $w_{asirt}$ denote the population at risk. We model deaths as draws from a Poisson distribution,
\begin{equation}
  y_{asirt} \sim \text{Poisson}(\gamma_{asirt} w_{asirt}) \label{eq:likelihood_baseline}
\end{equation}
where $\gamma_{asirt}$ is the mortality rate. 

We model each cell's (log) mortality rate based on its place within the classification by age, sex, indigenous status, state or territory, and year,
\begin{equation}
  \log \gamma_{asirt} \sim \text{N}(x_{asirt} \beta, \sigma^2). \label{eq:prior_model_baseline}
\end{equation}
Vector $\beta$ contains a combination of main effects and interactions, which are listed in Table~\ref{tab:priors_Baseline}. Vector $x_{asirt}$, which is  composed of 0s and 1s, assigns the appropriate elements of $\beta$ to each cell in the classification.

\input{out/tab_priors_Baseline}

Each main effect and interaction in \eqref{eq:prior_model_baseline} is provided with a prior distribution. We assume, for instance, that region effects follow an `exchangeable' prior of the form
\begin{equation}
  \beta_r^{\text{reg}} \sim \text{N}(0, \tau_{\text{reg}}^2).
\end{equation}
By using this prior we are essentially stating that mortality levels across states and territories are similar, though not identical.  The degree of similarity is governed by the parameter $\tau_{\text{reg}}$.  The time effect is given a `local trend' model \citep[][119--120]{prado2010time}, which is a generalization of a random walk with drift.  The age effect is given a similar prior: in statistical demography, smoothing over age is much like smoothing over time, so it makes sense to apply time series models to age effects.

In the course of building a model such as that of \eqref{eq:likelihood_baseline} and \eqref{eq:prior_model_baseline}, we inevitably make simplifying assumptions.  The model assumes, for instance, that, although the level of mortality experienced by indigenous people varies from region to region, the underlying age pattern does not.  In other words, the model does not include an age-indigenous-region interaction. We cannot have faith in the model until we have tested assumptions such as these.

One such test is to generate `replicate datasets' and compare these with the actual dataset. The replicate datasets are generated using the fitted values from our statistical model, except that the region effects and region-indigenous interactions are draw from their prior distributions. We compare the regional variation in age-patterns for these replicate datasets regional variation in the actual dataset. If the actual datasets appears distinctive in some way, we conclude that our model cannot adequately represent regional variation.

Our ultimate motivation for estimating mortality rates is to obtain reigonal life tables for indigenous people.  With Bayesian methods, obtaining estimates for derived quantities, such as life tables, is easy.

We carry out the estimation using our own open source \proglang{R} packages \pkg{dembase} and \pkg{demest}.

